items.creator: obj_319
items.summary: The 1990 Annual Report of Stichting Lobi (Love Foundation), the Family Planning Association of Suriname, has information about the demographic, health, and family planning background of Suriname, history and philosophy of the organization, long-term objectives, strategies, current projects and special activities, with photographs.  Since its founding in 1968, with major support from Dutch Development Aid, Lobi has opened 2 clinics, provided Pap smears, mounted education and mass media campaigns including a pop record in Surinamese and a sex education book for youths, conducted a KAP survey and an AIDS education campaign.  Lobi was one of the founding members of the Caribbean Family Planning Affiliation in 1971, and joined the IPPF in 1990.  Suriname gained independence from the Netherlands in 1975.  The country is composed of 37% East Indians, 31% Creoles, 15% Javanese and 1% Europeans.  75% of the people live in the capital, Paramaribo.  The infant mortality rate is 29.4/1000, the maternal mortality, 6.7/1000, life expectancy is 66.6 years.  There is no official government family planning policy, but the government cooperates with the family planning association in providing services in its clinics.  The long term objective is to improve quality of life and dignity of the family by improving the health of women and children.  The main strategies are to persuade the government to provide family planning and sex education; to develop special education and motivation programs for target groups; and to provide clinical services.  A project recently completed was a survey of single and married men:  both stated that the main aim of contraception is to allow women to be independent and to give men the opportunity to have several partners.

items.title: Antigens and antigen presentation in relation to vaccine development /
items.creator: obj_382
items.summary: Classification and analysis of antigens for development of vaccines are reviewed.  Of the 50 vaccines currently used in human and veterinary medicine, the most successful are live and attenuated viral antigens. Most attenuated virus are effective and long-lasting after a single dose, but may inactivated whole and subunit vaccines require multidoses. Bacterial vaccines include the attenuated BCG vaccine, less effective inactivated whole vaccines, and several subunit and toxoid vaccines. New approaches to vaccine development take into account knowledge of T and B cell dynamics.  Both types of lymphocytes recognize epitopes of 6-8 amino acids or 4-5 sugars.  B cells recognize intact antigens with a tertiary or quaternary shape on the Ig receptors at the B cell surface, but T cells recognize a major histocompatibility-peptide complex with a hydrophobic region at the surface of an antigen-presenting cell.  New possibilities for antigens include synthetic antigens (only in research stages), antigens produced through recombinant DNA (e.g., hepatitis B made in yeast, and several veterinary vaccines made in E. coli), recombinant live vectors (e.g., vaccinia, adenovirus, BCG, Salmonella). anti-idiotype antigens are theoretically possible and have been attempted with poliovirus type II and rabies.  New developments such as gene banks and monoclonal antibodies have greatly facilitated identification and isolation of candidates for vaccine antigens.  Ways to enhance the immunogenicity of simple antigens include new adjuvants, controlled release formulations, and recruitment of T-cells to help activate antigen-presenting cells.  Finally, new routes of administration will appear based on new knowledge of lymphocyte circulation.  Examples are oral administration of adenovirus vaccine, a virus that infects the respiratory tract, and the potential use of the oral route for organisms that infect the genital tract.

items.summary: The BioProcessing Module (BPM), Materials Dispersion Apparatus (MDA), and Fluid Processing Apparatus (FPA) were assessed for their ability to support tissue culture during space flight. Tissue used in the experiments was cultured mouse pre-metatarsal mesenchyme. Tissue analysis examined measurement of the length of the cartilage rods, detection of mineralized tissue, and observation of terminally differentiated chondrocytes. Only the rods grown in the FPA showed consistently longer growth in length and none of the systems supported cell differentiation or mineralization.

items.title: The biology and epidemiology of HIV-2 /
items.creator: obj_1013
items.summary: HIV-1 was identified before HIV-2.  Much of the virologic characterization of both types of HIV is therefore based upon research on HIV-1.  HIV-1 and HIV-2 are closely related human lentiviruses, with much of the virus-cell interactions, genetic structure, and overall morphology of HIV-2 resembling those of HIV-1.  The two viruses are, however, distinct viral types rather than different viral strains or variants.  Seroepidemiologic studies have found significant rates of HIV-2 infection in Africa, mainly in West Africa.  The virus has also been described in Angola, Mozambique, Tanzania, and sporadically in other African regions.  There are only extremely low HIV-2 infection rates in the US and Europe.  This paper discusses the cell tropism and viral receptors of HIV-2, formation and organization of the provirus, the regulation of proviral transcription, viral gene products, virion assembly and ultrastructure, epidemiology, and clinical outcome.  The rate of progression from seroconversion to US Centers for Disease Control stage IV disease appears to be 3-4 times faster in the case of infection with HIV-1 compared to infection with HIV-2.

items.title: Caveats associated with identifying HIV using transmission electron microscopy /
items.creator: obj_1221
items.summary: This article recommends caution in diagnosing the presence of human immunodeficiency virus (HIV) in human tissue by only using the procedure of transmission electron microscopy (TEM) as the sole analytical method.  Because of the difficulty in positively identifying the HIV virus with this method, the analysis can lead to erroneous conclusions if not confirmed by other methods.  A major limitation in the TEM method is the poor sampling size which results from examining ultra-thin sections (50- 80 nm) representing a small fraction of the tissue specimen being examined.  When the tissue is homogeneous, sampling size is not a problem; however, it becomes very significant when the tissue is heterogeneous os small particles of HIV (100-200 nm) are used.  The outcomes of several studies reveal these findings..

items.summary: Gravity exerts a fundamental influence on Earth organisms.  This will sound like a truism to many scientists, but the fact is that the importance of the gravitational force for life-sciences research was never really faced until the space age dawned.  Some very basic physical processes work quite differently under normal Earth gravity (1 g) and under so-called 'microgravity' conditions.  But it is not just that fundamental physical processes are different in microgravity:  since these physical processes are involved in many biological processes, biological systems may also be altered or affected in new ways.  While it is conceivable that a complex organism like a human body experiences a number of effects in a microgravity environment, it is much more difficult to accept that a single cell may perceive gravity.  Calculations based on the physical properties of the cell membrane, organelles and cytoskeleton seem to predict that no gravity effect may be expected at the cellular level.  However, most of these considerations look at the cell as a static and unchangeable system, and do not account for the countless single events occurring in sequence or in parallel in a living cell during differentiation, proliferation and gene expression.  All this machinery has developed under 1 g conditions, i.e. it is designed to make optimum use of gravity during differentiation, proliferation and gene expression.  Evolution at 1 g has probably ruled out the unfavourable alternative pathways leading to failures in the cellular functions.  The system did not have the chance to go through evolution at zero g and to exclude these unfavourable pathways.  The discussion on microgravity effects in the context of cell biology presented below is by no means complete:  only a few areas will be touched upon, but they have been chosen to demonstrate how microgravity will open up important new areas in the study of the life sciences.

items.summary: The purpose of this paper is to present the state-of-the-art on the behavior of single cells in culture under microgravity conditions.  Particular relevance is given to mammalian cells, including human.  After the analysis of the results obtained from experiments performed on recent Spacelab missions we know that single cells are sensitive to gravity.  Proliferation, membrane properties, biosynthesis and metabolism are changed when the gravitational environment is changed.  More basic research in space is required to understand the cellular mechanisms of adaptation to microgravity.  However, biotechnological applications of cell cultures in space can be envisaged already today.  It is not the scope of this paper to give a comprehensive review of all investigations performed with single cells in space.  We rather discuss here our own results and experimental approach to this subject.

items.summary: The purpose of the experiments conducted during the IML-1 mission was to determine the effects of the space flight environment on mitotic cell division, chromosome behaviour, and meiosis of diploid cells of the yeast Saccharomyces cerevisiae, a model unicellular eukaryote.  Two types of yeast cultures were flown:  mitotic cell cultures in which yeast cell populations are established by budding and mitosis, and meiotic cell cultures in which yeast cells undergo meiosis and ascospore formation.  The mitotic cell cultures are microbial analogs of the basic somatic mitotic cell division processes that occur in humans while meiotic cell cultures are microbial analogs of human meiosis and gamete formation.

items.creator: obj_2055
items.summary: This review of proto-oncogenes that function in spermatogenesis and oocyte maturation begins with a short introduction of oncogenes and proto-oncogenes in general.  Oncogenes were first identified in retroviruses, then as homologs of retroviral genes, as agents of transformation of cells in culture, and finally as genes involved in neoplasm.  The >60 oncogenes known encode proteins that act as growth factors, kinases, and plasma, membrane, and cytoplasmic signal transducing molecules.  Proto-oncogenes are the genes believed to have growth factor and regulatory functions in normal cells, that are rearranged or altered to become oncogenes.  Spermatogenesis is a process well suited for the study of proto-oncogenes, since cell types can be isolated easily in a spectrum of developmental stages from stem cell to mature spermatozoa.  Some proto-oncogenes identified in this process are c-abl tyrosine kinase, pim-a serin-threonine kinase, c-mos also a serine kinase, and int-1.  The authors studied c-raf, a serine-threonine kinase proto-oncogene and c-mos, both of which are expressed in all spermatogenic cells.  There are also several ras genes, which encode plasma membrane guanine nucleotide-binding proteins, expressed throughout spermatogenesis.  Nuclear proto-oncogenes c-myc, c-fos, and c-jun were active in type B spermatogonia, and c-myc and c-jun in preleptotene spermatocytes.  The genes c-jun and c-fox are now known to be nuclear transcription factors.  The c-mos gene is also a serine kinase in mouse oocytes, probably active in early development before the 2nd meiotic division.

items.title: Cellular sensation and responses to mechanical forces /
creator: obj_2118
obj_2119
obj_2120
items.summary: In a microgravity environment, human bodies experience dramatic biological changes such as bone loss, muscle atrophy, suppressed immune function, and altered cardiopulmonary functions.  However, cellular and molecular mechanisms that are responsible for these changes have remained elusive.  Gravity exerts its effects on human cells when it acts on macroscopic structures and becomes concentrated in masses such as bone and muscle.  In other words, cells likely experience gravity as a result of local changes in normal stresses and bending stresses that depend on the continuity of the entire tissue mass.  However, the cellular response to gravity must at some level involve the action of a mechanical force on an individual cell.  Thus, a key to understanding the effects of gravity on cells is development of methods to apply controlled mechanical forces directly to individual cells and to analyze the molecular basis of the cellular response.

items.title: Cellular tensegrity and mechanochemical transduction /
creator: obj_2145
obj_2146
obj_2147
items.summary: To explain how biological tissues form and function, we must first understand how different types of regulatory signals, both chemical and mechanical, integrate inside the cell.  A clue to the mechanism of signal integration comes from recognition that the action of a force on any mass, regardless of scale, will result in a change in three dimensional structure.  This is critical because recent studies reveal that many of the molecules that mediate signal transduction and stimulus-response coupling are physically bound to insoluble structural scaffoldings within the cytoskeleton and nucleus (Ingber 1993a).  In this type of "solid-state" regulatory system, mechanically-induced structural arrangements could provide a mechanism for regulating cellular biochemistry and hence, efficiently integrating structure and function.  However, this is a difficult question to address using conventional molecular biological approaches because this problem is not based on changes in chemical composition or local binding interactions.  Rather, it is a question of architecture.  As a result of this challenge, a new scientific discipline of "Molecular Cell Engineering" is beginning to emerge which combines elements of molecular cell biology, bioengineering, architecture, and biomechanics.  The purpose of this chapter is not to present a detailed analysis of the work from different laboratories that has contributed to this field since this has been recently published (Ingber 1993a,b).  Instead, I hope to provide a brief overview of recent work from my own laboratory which attempts to place biochemical mechanisms of regulation within the context of a specific architectural paradigm that is known as "tensegrity".  I also will explore the implications of this approach for cell biology as well as the future of engineering.

items.title: Cervical cancer screening in women attending a family planning clinic in Nairobi, Kenya /
items.creator: obj_2250
items.summary: The use potential of both aided and direct visual inspection with acetic acid (cervicoscopy) as cervical cancer screening tools was assessed in a 1994-95 study of 1050 women attending the Ribiero Family Planning Clinic in Nairobi, Kenya.  The mean age of study subjects was 29.7 years (range, 17-54).  171 women (19.8%) were positive for human papillomavirus; 115 (67.3%) of these cases were oncogenic and 45 (26.3%) could not be typed with certainty.  Pap testing revealed 57 cases (5.4%) of cervical intraepithelial neoplasia (CIN) type I, 28 cases (2.7%) of CIN II, 6 cases (0.6%) of CIN III, 9 cases (0.9%) of CIS, and 8 cases (0.8%) of invasive cancer; the frequencies of these diagnoses by histology, performed in a subset of 111 women, were 6.4%, 1.5%, 0.5%, 1.5%, and 0.7%, respectively.  There was no consistent relationship between previous Pap testing and current disease status.  Among women with a normal Pap test, 53% had been screened previously and 60% of these women received a normal result.  52% of women with high-grade lesions or cancer had received a Pap test earlier and 57% claimed their test was normal.  129 women had evidence of high-grade lesions or cancer according to cervicoscopy, for a sensitivity of 26.0%, a specificity of 88.0%, and a positive predictive value of 4.6%.  Gynoscopy increased sensitivity to 75.0%, but decreased specificity to 67.7% and the positive predictive value fell to 2.1%.  These findings indicate a need for further refinement of cervical cancer screening techniques.  While use of histology is associated with underdetection of high-grade cases, a visualize-and-treat approach would produce considerable overtreatment.

items.summary: Between June 1991 and February 1992 in Senegal, physicians enrolled 102 female patients of the Infectious Disease Department of Fann Hospital, part of the University Cheikh Anta Diop in Dakar, in a case control study to find out whether there is an association between HIV infection and cervical dysplasia.  66 women were HIV seronegative.  18 and 17 women were HIV-1 and HIV-2 seropositive, respectively.  1 woman was seropositive for HIV-1 and HIV-2.  Divorced women were more likely to be HIV seropositive than currently married women (73% vs. 24%; p = .000009).  Parity, oral contraceptive use, and age at first intercourse were not significantly associated with HIV infection.  Most seropositive women had CDC class IV cervical dysplasia (67% for HIV-1 and 77% for HIV-2).  HIV seropositive women were 11.6 times more likely to develop cervical dysplasia than seronegative women, suggesting considerable immunosuppression and, therefore, advanced HIV disease.  Polymerase chain reaction was 10.8 times more likely to detect human papilloma virus (HPV) infection in HIV seropositive women than in HIV seronegative women.  Oncogenic HPV types 16/18 and 31/33/35 were in 45.7% of HIV seropositive women but only in .06% of HIV seronegative women.  HPV DNA existed in 80% of women with abnormal Pap smears compared to 35% of women with normal cytology (p < .005).  In conclusion, a positive association exists between HIV infection and cervical dysplasia in Senegalese women.  The results indicated that health workers should often conduct cytologic screening in HIV seropositive women and treat dysplasia lesions appropriately.

John Gleason of the Center for Science in the Public Interest (CSPI) explains how this diet affects the children who eat the food. The third segment, "Fishing Expedition" with reporter Phil Jones, discusses the health issues of seafood restaurants with CSPI researchers Michael Jacobson and Jane Hurley. They explain how the research is done. The fourth segment, "Feast or Famine II", reports on how the people in segment one actually did on a healthy eating scale.  The fifth segment, "Fat Chance" with reporter Susan Spencer, looks at fat free foods. One person who eats nothing but low fat or fat free foods is profiled. A nutritionist examines the strengths and weaknesses of the diet.  The sixth segment, "Wonder Bread" with reporter Erin Moriarity, describes bread products made by Natural Ovens Bakery. "Brainy Bagels" are donated to an elementary school and their impact on the children is conveyed.  Paul Stitt, the founder of Natural Ovens bakery, is interviewed, and he describes why this bread is healthier than other breads. The reason he cites is the use of flax seed in the bread. Flax seed is an omega-3 fatty acid which helps the cardiovascular system. Nutritionist Phyllis Bowen says that research does not support the benefits outlined by Mr. Stitt.

items.titleStatement: H. Creed-Kanashiro, M. Fukumoto, M.E. Ugaz.
items.summary: A project was conducted in 1989-92 in nine marginal urban areas of Lima to determine whether a community education campaign in infant nutrition could produce improvements in infant nutrition practices.  Inadequate food consumption and a high incidence of infectious illnesses are associated with a high frequency of growth deficiencies in young Peruvian children.  In the first project phase, mothers, midwives, and health workers were interviewed concerning their feeding practices and the nutritional advice given to new mothers.  Mothers were found to worry that their milk supply was insufficient.  A number of harmful feeding practices were identified, such as the initiation of herbal infusions or teas in the first month of life and the preference for soups and other foods of thin consistency and inadequate energy density.  A breast feeding campaign was designed to increase maternal confidence and knowledge, while a supplementary feeding campaign sought to increase knowledge of infant nutritional needs.  The mothers were highly motivated to improve their feeding practices.  Posters, short videos, pamphlets, and recipes were distributed, and short radio spots were aired.  Short training courses and demonstrations of food preparation were the central features of the campaign.  28 courses on breast feeding were attended by 479 mothers, and 29 courses of supplementary feeding were attended by 430 mothers.  Program evaluation was based on interviews, a survey of 10% of households, and observations of infants under and over 5 months old to detect possible changes in feeding practices.  The proportion of infants under 4 months old being exclusively breast fed increased from 32.7% before to 43.1% after the campaign, while the average duration of exclusive breast feeding increased from 17 days to 5 weeks.  The proportion of infants given herbal infusions and teas at 1 month declined from 82% before to 57% after the campaign.  The proportion of infants aged 6-12 months who were adequately fed was estimated to have increased from 15.2% before to 27.9% after the campaign.

items.title: Anemia and iron interventions for preschool children in the Philippines /
items.creator: obj_4414
items.summary: Anemia among infants and preschool children is a serious public health problem in the Philippines.  An imbalance between dietary iron supply and the increasing iron needs of young children during periods of rapid growth is assumed to be the major cause of anemia.  The current Philippine Plan of Action for Nutrition gives priority to provision of pharmaceutical iron supplements to pregnant women, infants, and preschoolers.  The next step is for the Department of Health to recommend a suitable iron supplement.  Fortification of rice and other food products with ferrous sulfate represents a potential strategy in areas where anemia is widespread.  Another approach is to reduce consumption of iron absorption inhibitors and promote intake of absorption enhancers such as vitamin C and heme iron.  Parents can be taught to modify their infant's diet by preparing complementary foods rich in iron and vitamin C, including purees of raw fruits and cooked vegetables.  The Filipino mass media are broadcasting messages promoting foods rich in micronutrients.  The basic goal of dietary modification and education programs in the Philippines remains to persuade parents to feed their children well-balanced meals.

items.title: Aplicaciones en epidemiologia nutricional /
items.creator: obj_4624
note: Presented at the 2nd Congreso Multidisciplinario Centro Medico Militar, Simposium de Nutricion y Dietetica: Avances en la Evaluacion Nutricional en Clinica, October 13-18, 1997.
items.summary: Development in the field of nutritional epidemiology showed that certain diets could influence the occurrence of disease in humans (e.g., the consumption of fruits and fresh vegetables could cure scurvy).  Definition of nutritional epidemiology includes the aspect of quantification of occurrence of disease, the description of those with diseases, and what are the alimentary and nutritional determinants of disease.  There are various indicators used in nutritional epidemiology.  Food-related/alimentary indicators measure diet and consumption (e.g., some Mediterranean countries have very low rates of chronic diseases and high life expectancy, purportedly owing to a diet low in saturated fats and containing plenty of fruits and vegetables).  Anthropometric indicators measure weight for height, weight for age, and height for age and are used for nutritional interventions, the evaluation of malnutrition or excess nutrition, and for the surveillance of the nutrition of the population.  Biochemical indicators can describe someone's nutritional condition or predict disease and are used for the evaluation of food supplementation (e.g., assessing the effect of biscuits fortified with bovine hemoglobin on the iron level of school-age children in Chile).

items.summary: This work describes the structure and nutritional content of cereals and the characteristics and uses of the most important grains, suggests recipes, and provides guidelines for selection and storage.  Cereals, like maize, wheat, rice, barley, and oats, are the seeds of cultivated grasses that contain a rich source of nutrients.  Cereals constitute the principal source of energy in the diets of developing countries due to their high-energy content and relatively low cost.  Cereals are consumed in the natural state or processed and as feed for livestock.  They are easy to cultivate and transport and may be stored for long periods.  Maize continues to be the basic food in the diet of the majority of Central and South America.  Cereal grains share similar structures, although their chemical compositions differ.  The outer husk is high in cellulose, which forms part of the nondigestible fiber.  It protects the germ and endosperm.  The germ contains protein, iron, niacin, thiamin, riboflavin, and a high percentage of fat, so that it easily becomes rancid and is usually removed before flour is made.  The nutritional value of cereals depends primarily on their high carbohydrate content, which ranges from 58% to 72%.  8-13% is protein, 2-5% fat, 10-14% water, and 2-11% nondigestible fiber.  Whole grains are a good source of thiamin and fiber.  Cereals provide 300-350 calories per 100 g.  Their nutritional value improves when they are combined with legumes or other foods that provide the amino acids lacking in cereals.

items.summary: The nutritional content, characteristics, selection, preparation, and storage of eggs are described.  The term egg usually refers to those of hens, but eggs of other domestic or wild birds and of turtles and fish are also eaten. A hen's egg weighs approximately 50-60 g, depending on the variety. 60% is egg white, 30% is yolk, and 10% is shell and membranes. The yolk contains more calories and minerals than the white. The main minerals are iron, calcium, phosphorus and sulfur. The water-soluble vitamins in the yolk are thiamin and riboflavin. Nearly all the fat and cholesterol and the fat-soluble vitamins A and D are in the yolk. Adults should limit egg consumption to avoid cholesterol. Egg yolks are excellent for children over 6 months old because of their iron content. Egg white is composed almost entirely of protein and water, with some riboflavin. The proteins in eggs are in a colloidal solution and easily digestible by small children or convalescents. Protein from eggs is of superior quality. A whole egg is fresh if its sinks in a glass of water and on examination in strong light its air pocket has not enlarged and its yolk remains in the center. A shelled egg is fresh if the yolk is bulging, centrally positioned and rounded, and the white is viscous and firm. Intense and prolonged heat should be avoided in cooking eggs. It is recommended that eggs be cooked to avoid salmonella and similar problems.

items.summary: This work describes the nutritional content, characteristics, selection, storage, and uses of meats consumed by humans. Animals of Central America that are rarely consumed, such as the armadillo, rabbit, or iguana, have equal or greater protein content than beef, pork, or chicken, a lower price, and less fat. Meats differ in color, consistency, and fat content. White meat has less connective tissue. Red meats contain more of the cholesterol and saturated fat associated with heart disease. The color of meat gives an idea of its fat content and the age of the animal, and the odor indicates freshness. Along with milk and eggs, meat is the major source of high-quality protein for formation and growth of the body's tissues and muscles. Meats are 15-20% protein, depending on the type and cut. Proteins from meats provide all the essential amino acids in suitable proportions for the body to form its own protein.  Meats are 5-40% fat; fat content largely determines their caloric content. All meats are very good sources of B complex vitamins and to a lesser degree of thiamin. Meats with less fat are an excellent source of iron and phosphorus and those with bone also provide calcium. The liver is especially rich in iron and vitamin A, but the viscera are high in cholesterol. Sausages have high salt and fat content and should not be consumed to excess. Refrigeration is the most practical means of storing meat.

items.title: Abnormal secretion of prolactin and pathogenesis of galactorrhoea /
items.creator: obj_5006
items.summary: Although the existence of prolactin as a pituitary hormone distinct from growth hormone in man has been questioned for many years, this hormone has now been isolated and purified. The recent development of sensitive radioimmunoassays specific for measurement of human prolactin in small aliquots of blood allowed the study of regulation and pathology of its secretion. In the present study, human prolactin was measured in a "homologous" ovine radioimmunoassay. Basal prolactin levels were found to be elevated in a few cases of acromegaly, in congenital myxoedema (athyreosis), in patients with prolactin-secreting tumours and in many cases of galactorrhoea and of amenorrhoea-galactorrhoea syndromes. Hypophysectomy for prolactin-secreting tumours usually did not result in abolition of prolactin. Patients with hypopituitarism were classified along their basal prolactin levels (low - normal - elevated). Although more individuals than expected had prolactin levels above the upper 95% confidence limit of normal values, mean prolactin for both hypothyroids and hyperthyroids was within the normal range. Basal prolactin was found unaltered in postmenopausal women with advanced breast cancer. The pathogenesis of puerperal lactation and abnormal galactorrhea was discussed: although prolactin appears to be essential for the onset and maintenance of lactation, a hormonal lactogenic complex is involved at least in non-puerperal galactorrhoea. A preliminary evaluation of the TRH and L-dopa tests is presented for the assessment of the hypothalamo pituitary axis and the differential diagnosis between functional versus tumoural hyperprolactinaemia. It has been found that TRH-induced prolactin release is abolished or at least reduced in acromegaly, hypopituitarism and prolactin-secreting tumours.

items.summary: Abortion and premature labor are discussed.  Abortion, immature infants, premature infants, spontaneous, induced and therapeutic abortion, crimal abortion and complete, incomplete, and missed abortion are all defined.  Spontaneous abortion is discussed in terms of incidence, etiology (abnormal development of the fetus, abnormaltities of the placenta, and maternal disease), pathology (blood or carneous mole, tuberous mole, dissolution), clinical aspects, and  treatment (for threatened abortion, inevitable abortion, incomplete abortion, and missed abortion).  Habitual abortion is defined and discussed as well, focusing on etiology, faulty maternal environment, clinical investigation, and prognosis.  The serious complications of abortion are frequently associated with illegal procedures.  Such  complications include fibrility, infection, hemorrhage, bacterial endotoxic shock, and acute renal failure.  Premature birth is the most common cause of neonatal mortaility and morbidity.  In only about 40% of patients can the cause of prematurity be demonstrated.  Management of premature labor is discussed.

items.title: Amenorrhoea and oligomenorrhoea /
creator: obj_5310
obj_5311
items.summary: When there has never been any blood lost from the uterus, the state is one of primary amenorrhea.  The diagnosis of the cause of amenorrhea may involve careful history taking, x-ray studies of the pituitary gland fossa, hormone and biochemical investigations, laparoscopy, and chromosome studies.  The history taking is to determine to what extent and at what age any vaginal bleeding has occurred and the secondary sexual characteristics first appeared.  In the physical examination stature, hair distribution, breast development, genital organ development, and behavior are all carefully observed and noted.  In the hormone investigations the quantities of serum follicle stimulating hormones, luteinizing hormone, and serum progesterone and total estrogens and 17 ketosteroid and hydroxycorticoid excretions in the urine in 24 hours are ascertained twice with 14-day intervals between to see whether there is any cyclical variation.  If chromosome material is excessive or deficient, normal development is affected.  Large chromosome abnormalities, being accompanied by major developmental defects, may lead to abortion, still birth, or early neonatal death.  Relatively minor degrees of defect in the sex chromosomes lead to faulty sex structure of function.  The possible chromosome combinations that can exist in the patient who does not menstruate but who has female external genitalia and has been sexed and brought up as a girl are listed in a table.  Among the causes of secondary amenorrhea in patients with the normal 44 plus XX complement of chromosomes, postpill amenorrhea and postpartum amenorrhea, both of which may be associated with galactorrhea, are frequently found.  They enter the differential diagnosis of amenorrhea and oligomenorrhea as does the Stein Leventhal syndrome.  Arrhenoblastoma similarly must be considered, especially when there is evidence of masculinization.  Many generalized diseases may give rise to amenorrhea and especially to be mentioned are thyroid hormone diseases and psychological upsets, particularly depression, whether endogenous or dictated by external circumstances.  The following are common causes of secondary oligomenorrhea which may sometimes become amenorrhea:  postpill; dieting which may progress to anorexia nervosa; the Stein Leventhal syndrome; thyroid, pituitary, adrenal disturbances; and hyperprolactinemia.  On stopping oral contraception (OC), menstruation may not return, or if it does, it is scanty and very irregular.  A large proportion of these patients if left completely alone will within 5 or 6 months recover spontaniously their previous pattern, which often was of irregular mensturation.  Strict dieting will usually result in amenorrhea.  Usually once the particular stresses have been overcome or understood properly, mensturation and fertility return.

items.summary: The Pan American Health Organization, in close collaboration with UNICEF and the International Council for Control of Iodine Deficiency Diseases, conducted a review of the literature and recent reports to provide current information on the status and trends of iodine deficiency disorders and control programs and their effectiveness.  The study was conducted to assess the magnitude and gravity of the endemic, bottlenecks impeding elimination, and lessons learned in successful  programs. Interagency coordination to aid in control efforts was also examined.  The different sections of the report provide background on the prevalence of goiter and other iodine deficiency diseases, previous efforts at control, and related research.  Epidemiological criteria for estimating the severity of iodine deficiency disorders as a public health problem are then described.  The results are presented in terms of the prevalence of goiter, urinary excretion of iodine, iodization of salt, national legislation regarding the obligation to fortify salt with iodine, action strategies for elimination of iodine deficiency disorders in 17 countries, and interagency coordination.  Reports from 20 individual countries are also presented, with information on recent studies of goiter and urinary excretion of iodine, availability of iodized salt and iodine compounds, and action strategies in each country.  Other sections present overall conclusions and suggestions for future action.

items.title: An assessment of prophylactic programs :
creator: obj_5519
obj_5520
items.summary: There continues to be a lag between the availability of knowledge and its application to the prevention of endemic goiter and endemic cretinism.  Both conditions have been shown to be preventable by iodization programs in all parts of the world.  The reasons for delay in the implementation of iodization programs constitute the subject of this review.  Apart from technological considerations, this review identifies the need for an understanding of the social processes involved in the establishment of public health programs at every stage of a country's development.  Evidence related to these social processes is examined, and an attempt is made to develop a model indicating the relationship between political, social, and legal factors.  Programs in the various World Health Organization (WHO) regions are reviewed initially--Europe, North America, Central and South America, New Zealand, Tasmania, Papua New Guinea, Africa, and Southeast Asia.  Some countries have not legislated a program; others have not implemented legislation passed many years ago.  The reasons given for failure of iodization programs in South America include political factors, the geographic isolation of goiter areas, and difficulties in the production of iodized salt.  Political, social, cultural, and economic factors are all relevant.  The model suggested to aid in the understanding of the social and political processes involved in the application of available knowledge in the field of public health includes a series of 7 sequential steps:  collection of epidemiological data on the prevalence of goiter and cretinism; analysis with a view toward dissemination in the mass media; the planning of an iodization program; political agreement before legislation; implementation; and evaluation based on the collection of further survey data on the prevalence of goiter and cretinism in the hope of demonstrating its reduction.  The data should then be fed back to the community to demonstrate the benefits of the program and the need for its continuity.  Demonstrable failure of the program leads to investigation of the causes so that the public can be informed and there can be further discussion of appropriate measures to overcoming the obstacles.  The process involves a continuous feedback to the community.  This ensures ongoing interest and support.  The 2 steps in the social process that are most commonly associated with delay are the failure to disseminate information to the community through the mass media and the problem of implementation.

items.title: At risk aspects of metabolic effects of oral contraceptives /
creator: obj_5565
obj_5566
items.summary: The adverse effects of oral contraceptives are reviewed by categorizing the combined pills by chemical family of progestin.  Virtually all combined pills now contain the synthetic estrogen ethinyl estradiol.  The progestins in the pills exert metabolic effects primarily by their antiestrogenic and progestogenic effects.  The pregnane family of progestins have disappeared from the market because of their side effects in beagle bitches, breast dysplasia and carbohydrate abnormalities.  Only cyproterone acetate is still used in a formulation called Diane, prescribed for women with androgenic complaints.  The estranes, all metabolized to norethisterone, have mainly anti-estrogenic properties, and are prescribed for women with menorrhagia.  The gonanes include the racemic mixture norgestrel, the active racemic levonorgestrel, and several newer progestins, desogestrel, norgestimate, and gestodene.  Desogestrel has the unique property of increasing sex hormone binding globulin.  All the new progestins are relatively neutral in their sex steroid effects and metabolic effects, while potently inhibiting gonadotropins.  The adverse metabolic effects of oral contraceptives, increased coagulation, lipoproteins, atherogenesis, hypertension and diabetes are all documented only in Caucasian women consuming Western diets.  Venous thromboembolism is directly related to dose of estrogen, and associated with norethynodrel and the pregnane- containing products.  Levonorgestrel and gonane pills do not significantly affect coagulation.  Atherogenic lipid changes are related to progestins, but biologically significant effects are probably more likely if the woman is sedentary, obese, older, and especially if she smokes.  Hypertension develops in a small percentage of all women who use the pill, who were probably predisposed.  Oral contraception should not necessarily be discontinued, however, since pregnancy could be a far greater risk.  Insulin resistance and abnormal glucose tolerance also occurs in predisposed women who use the pill.  It should be kept in mind that many of these findings normalize with duration of use: rest from the pill is no longer advised.

creator: obj_5933

items.summary: Changes in the reproductive tract related to long term use of oral contraceptives are reviewed.  Because of the difficulties of direct observation, it is difficult to draw valid conclusions about the effects of oral contraceptives on the ovaries.  To date, there is no accurate way of assessing the effects of oral contraceptives on gonadotropin excretion.  Epithelial changes in the vagina are thought to be due to the combined effects of endogenous and exogenous steroids.  In the cervix, the primary effect of progesterones is to alter the cervical mucus and thus provide a barrier to sperm penetration.  The overall effect of combined oral contraceptives on the oviducts and breasts.  In assessing general metabolic and endocrine effects, it is difficult to completely separate psychogenic effects from purely physiological effects.  Commonly noted side effects include nausea, dizziness, headaches, breakthrough bleeding, mastalgia, weight change and melanosis, and Central Nervous System effects which include emotional changes which may be related to hormonal changes.  There have been varying reports of hematologic effects and effects on carbohydrate, lipid and thyroid metabolism.  Effects on blood coagulation and thrombophlebitis and the liver are reviewed.

items.summary: Factors involved in normal growth and development of the breast, including the physiology of normal lactation and the role of prolactin therein, are reviewed.  Galactorrheic syndromes, which constitute inappropriate lactation, are characterized, and considerations for differential diagnosis of galactorrhea are listed.  The clinical problems associated with galactorrhea, such as prolonged and zealous follow-up, have been alleviated somewhat by the polytomography technique now available for discovering the presence of a pituitary tumor, a common cause of galactorrhea.  Methods of differential diagnosis include: 1) clinical evidence of other tropic hormone losses (hypothyroidism, hypoadrenalism, or hypogonadism);  2) the prolactin assay, which serves 2 purposes: measurement of basal prolactin levels is helpful in following response to treatment, and extremely elevated levels are more likely to be associated with pituitary tumors;  and 3) polytomography.  Galactorrhea treatment methods are summarized.  Since 1 of 15 women will develop breast cancer during her lifetime, the chapter concludes with a discussion of risk factors (reproductive experience, ovarian activity, benign breast disease, familial tendency, genetic differences, and specific endocrine factors) and recommended treatments of this disease.

items.title: Chairman's summary /
items.creator: obj_6454
items.summary: American women used oral contraceptives at the rate of 8.5 million cycles per month in 1969, double the 1965 rate.  The use-effectiveness of combined tablets (80% of all used) was .7 pregnancies per 100 users per year;  for sequentials, it was 1.4.  A relative risk (users to nonusers) of thromboembolic disorders was 4.4 in the United States.  Carcinogenicity of oral contraceptives could not be affirmed or denied, although much evidence supported the carcinogenic effects of estrogen.  There was no evidence that the many systemic metabolic changes produced by the pill posed serious health hazards, but much basic information about them was lacking.  Recommendations were for 1) case-controlled studies on breast and uterine cancer like those done for thromboembolism, 2) basic research into metabolic effects, 3) development of new birth control methods, and 4) improvements in Food and Drug Administration surveillance, local reporting of adverse effects, and fertility statistics.  Oral contraceptives were pronounced safe, in the sense of having a sufficiently high ratio of benefit to risk.

items.summary: The clinical aspects of oral gestogens are summarized in this WHO technical report.  Medical considerations of the various oral contraceptives are reviewed.  Research findings on the effects of oral gestogens on the endocrine glands, generative organs and breasts, systemic conditions, and the fetus and subsequent fertility are reviewed.  Formulations and dosage levels are dicussed in relation to effectiveness and side effects, and contraindications to oral contraceptive use are noted.  Considerations in examination and management of oral contraceptive users are given.  The needs of further research on oral contraceptive  effects in specific areas are outlined.  Recommendations and suggestions on the World Health Organization's role in world oral contraceptive use are set forth.  It is concluded that combined estrogen-progestogen preparations are virtually 100% effective as contraceptives, that associated side effects are usually not pathologically significant, and that a causal relation between various serious  diseases and oral contraceptives has not been demonstrated.

items.summary: This film, from the Yale Clinic of Child Development, Arnold Gesell, M.D., director, illustrates the retarded adaptive behavior of several children who suffer from cerebral injury, pseudo-symptomatic retardation, and untreated thyroid disease.  A forty-week-old infant with mild selective cerebral injury is shown nude and supine.  He tries to but can't grasp a large ring dangled above his chest until it touches his hand.  He is pulled to a sitting position but cannot sit alone or even hold his head up.  He slumps in a support chair and awkwardly picks up cubes put in front of him.  He shows poor thumb opposition.  At two and a half years this child stacks eight or ten blocks and works a simple puzzle.  He lurches and stumbles as he stands, walks, and plays with a ball.  A two-year-old child with severe selective cerebral injury sits in a man's lap and is held upright by him.  He looks at pictures in a book, then loses interest.  He does not try to pick up objects placed in front of him, but leans forward and mouths the object.  He cannot walk.  A two-year-old with pseudo-symptomatic retardation sits unsupported in a woman's lap.  As objects are presented to him, he touches them and then snatches his hand away.  He tries to work a simple puzzle but cannot.  A forty-six-week-old child with an untreated thyroid condition is shown sitting in a support chair making aimless movements with blocks, drooling, and awkwardly picking up a bell.  After fourteen weeks of therapy she is shown, in split-screen images, at forty-six weeks and sixty weeks.  After therapy she is more alert and more deft at handling objects.  At twenty months, after forty weeks of therapy, she exhibits the behavior of a seventeen-month-old.

items.title: Clinical studies (Oral contraceptives) /
items.creator: obj_6987
items.summary: Clinical studies on the effects of oral contraceptives are discussed.  A majority of 726 subjects taking Enovid or Ovulen noted no change in breast size.  Alleged increases and decreases in breast size were about equal except for the highest Enovid dosage where a fair proportion reported some breast size increase.  Reports of breast cycle discomfort in the first medication cycle have varied.  Data have indicated that lactation tends to be diminished in subjects using higher doses of Enovid.  Several of the steroidal agents used for fertility control have been used in the treatment of inoperable metastatic breast cancer.  The use of synthetic progestins in pregnancy has been challenged because of their masculinizing effects on the female fetus.  Transmission of synthetic steroids through the milk has been suggested by significant skeletal advancement seen in 5 of 6 infants whose mothers were taking Pranone or Norlutin and gynecomastia in a male infant breastfed by a mother using  Enovid for contraception.  Conversely, no signs of hormonal effect were seen in a large number of infants being nursed by Enovid users in Puerto Rico.  The effects of ovarian hormones upon the thyroid and the adrenal cortex have been investigated.  An increase in protein-bound iodine was noted in the blood of Enovid users.  The diminished carbohydrate tolerance observed in certain subjects taking Enovid may be attributed to the heightening of the glycosuric effect of cortisol observed on estrogen administration and noted in a diabetic woman taking Anovlar.

items.title: Complications of goiter prophylaxis /
items.creator: obj_7194
items.summary: Under conditions of goiter prophylaxis, iodine, an essential nutrient, has been shown to have adverse effects.  Reactions usually occur in susceptible individuals after a single or chronic dose of pharmacological doses of organic or inorganic iodine compounds.  Iodinated x-ray contrast media are most often responsible for 3 types of iatrogenic complications:  allergic reactions, iodine toxicity, and thyroidal disorders.  Chronic administration can produce the same types of complications.  Allergic reactions were reported in 168 of 10,000 intravenous urographies reviewed.  Toxic reactions were observed in 16% of the 502 patients being treated for bronchial asthma.  Thyroid disorders observed after large chronic doses of iodine include:  iodide goiter, Hashimotos's thyroiditis, iodide-thyroiditis, and iodine-induced hyperthyroidism (jodbasedow).  Pseudohyperthyroidism may occur after cholecystography.  In susceptible individuals, iodine treatment for hyperthyroidism may cause hypothyroidism.  Desirable nutritional intake is about 100-300 mcg/day.  Maximum safe daily intake is about 1000 mcg.  High nutritional intake of 500-3000 mcg/day over several weeks may have adverse effects in susceptible individuals, and has been linked to thyroid diseases such as, Hashimoto's thyroiditis, thyrotoxicosis, and iodide goiter.  Links with thyroid carcinoma are suspected in Japan, Iceland, and Hawaii.  Iodized oil has been used prophylactically in several endemias; New Guinea, Zaire, Ecuador, Peru, Nepal, and Portugal.  The results of the programs are mixed; some studies report an absence of complications and a reduction in the prevalence of goiter and cretinism, others report several instances of jodbasedow.  In Tasmania, studies of the introduction of iodized bread, containing optimal levels of iodine recommended for daily intake, reported an increased incidence of hyperthyroidism primarily among individuals over 40 years of age.  The development of 3 types of hyperthyroidism were noted:  Graves' disease with thyroid stimulating autoantibodies, toxic autonomous adenoma, and diffuse micronodular goiter with natural tendency toward formation of autonomous hot nodules.  Study results seem to indicate that every type of iodine nutrition and prophylaxis can contribute to abnormal thyroid hormonogenesis.  In health, serum levels of thyroid hormones do not fluctuate in response to environmental demands.  The regulation system of thyroid function either preserves the constancy of the thyroid hormone or serves as a safeguard from hypothyroidism.

items.title: Control de los desordenes por deficiencia de yodo en Centroamerica.
creator: obj_7331
obj_7332
note: Publicacion INCAP DCE/007. Editor: Samuel Estrada Duque.
items.summary: This study of control of iodine deficiency disorders in Central America contains three self-contained sections that examine prevalence of goiter, legislation regarding iodizing of salt, and production and marketing of iodized salt.  The situation in Guatemala, El Salvador, Honduras, Nicaragua, Costa Rica and Panama is separately examined in each section using the same format, in order to identify similarities as bases for regional corrective action.  Goiter is endemic in Central America, and iodine ingestion is deficient.  Only 12% of the salt consumed in the region meets international standards for iodizing.  The average prevalence of goiter in Central America is 14.3% overall, 16% in urban areas, and 13.2% in rural areas, and is tending to increase.  The six countries have a sufficient legal-juridical apparatus to assure effective iodizing of salt, defined as over 30 parts per million in regions of high endemicity.  Consumption of iodized salt is limited because regulation is lacking, and because human, technical, and economic resources are limited. Lack of knowledge about iodine deficiency disorders on the part of the consumers and the desire to cut costs of producing salt are other factors.  The six countries should share experiences to systematize legislation and make it operational through adequate regulation and creation of National Programs of Salt Iodization within health ministries.  Governments should provide economic assistance to salt producers and establish laboratories to monitor the iodization and quality of salt.  Most salt production in Central America is inefficient and unhygienic, based on evaporation of seawater through action of the sun, but production is relatively sufficient.  Most producers, processors, and distributors are unaware of the vital importance of iodizing salt, and should be informed about it.

items.title: Copper in mammalian reproduction /
creator: obj_7430
obj_7431
items.summary: This extensive book chapter covers all aspects of copper in mammalian reproduction.  Clinical aspects, mode of contraceptive action, and side effects of copper IUDs are discussed.  Hormonally induced changes in copper levels including ceruloplasmin, other oxidases, and effects on taste and smell are characterized and explained.  Copper-induced ovulation and releasing hormones and the influence of copper on sex steroid metabolism, prostaglandins, and thyroid constitute another set of major topics.  The role of copper in pregnancy falls under the following headings: 1) copper deficiency and reproductive failure;  2) copper-chelating agents and fetal resorption;  3) teratogenesis of related drugs, environmental toxins, and lathyrogenic agents;  4) copper excess;  and 5) copper in parturition.  The spermicidal action of copper and of chelating agents is explained, and the relationship of copper on neonatal and infant nutrition and hereditary diseases is outlined.  And discussion of the role of copper antagnists (zinc and vitamins) and excess copper in the environment ends this large review.
